## Emergency Escape

When JavaScript hits the word **`break`**, it instantly destroys the loop and continues running the rest of the file. It does not check the condition; it just leaves.

Imagine searching through 1,000 lottery tickets for the winning number. Once you find it on ticket 4, you don't need to check the other 996 tickets! You just break out.

```javascript
for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
  if (i === 5) {
    break; // Loop dies here!
  }
  console.log(i);
}
// Output: 1, 2, 3, 4
```

## Skipping the Boring Parts

The **`continue`** keyword is different. It doesn't destroy the loop. Instead, it instantly skips the rest of the code block FOR THIS ONE ITERATION, and jumps back to the top to start the next iteration.

Imagine dealing cards to players but skipping the dealer:

```javascript
for (let player = 1; player <= 5; player++) {
  if (player === 3) {
    continue; // Skips player 3 completely!
  }
  console.log("Dealing to player " + player);
}
// Output: Deals to 1, 2, 4, 5
```

